## Donâ€™t use color alone to convey information

Color can be useful to indicate statuses or other information to users. However, color alone should not be the only way information is conveyed as people who are colorblind may perceive the ifnormation differently.

When using color to differentiate elements, also provide additional information that does not rely on color perception. For example, use an asterisk or text in addition to color to indicate required form fields, and use labels to distinguish areas on graphs.

You must also ensure when using text on colored backgrounds, you are meeting [minimum contrast ratios](#provide-sufficient-contrast-between-foreground-and-background).

### Guidance for meeting this standard

<a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/use-of-color" target="_blank">WCAG 1.4.1 - Use of color - Level A</a>

### Tools you can use

